  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of people I know. Growing up in Rome, I was always the kid who loved fixing things with my hands, but my parents, both educated, never pushed me toward science or engineering. My older brother, who has a master's degree, often joked that I was 'too practical' for the academic world, which made me feel like I didn't belong in places where people talk about theories and equations. That's when I started to internalize the idea that if I tried to engage with STEM, I'd be judged as 'not smart enough.' Now, as a self-employed plumber, I see this dynamic every day. When I'm working on a project, I don't want to be the one who's 'the only one who doesn't fit'—but that's the reality for so many people. Stereotype threat is real, and it's not just about being afraid of failing; it's about the fear of being seen as less capable than others. We need to address it by creating spaces where people feel safe to explore STEM without the pressure of proving themselves. For me, that means starting small—like encouraging kids in my community to try hands-on projects, not just theoretical ones. It's not about fixing everyone's minds; it's about building confidence through real-world experiences. The problem isn't that people are bad at STEM—it's that they're afraid to try because they've been told they don't belong. And that's something we all need to change, starting with ourselves.",
